As the conflict between our scientific knowledge and our understanding of
ourselves as reasoning beings became more apparent, however, it was our
knowledge of necessary truths that appeared more difficult to explain. In the
case of knowledge justified by experience, there is, at least
when things go well, a causal chain running from external objects to experiences
and thence to the formation of beliefs true of those objects.
Modern philosophers may delight in considering abberant cases, fall into despair
