== philosophical movements ==
Every major philosophical movement since Descartes (with the possible exception
of Marxism) has been based around an attempt to answer the question of how our
knowledge of necessary truths is justified.

The British empiricists Locke, Berkeley and Hume, had no common account of our
knowledge of necessary truths, but they each extensively noted the difficulty in
explaining our knowledge of such truths unless they were vacuous. Hume, in
particular, explained our belief that some truths were necessary as due to
psychological mechanisms responding to empirically accessible properties such as
contiguity, succession and constant conjunction.

